Defines the data model and construction logic for Pass B's `@type` append set — the pool of types available to fill `%t` slots during expansion.

`TypeDef` represents one appendable type: its stroke, arity, rendered text (literal chunks plus `%t` markers), and a `free_type` flag for the empty/SKP case (arity-0, empty text) that leaves a bare `: ` and tabstop for hand-typing. `TypeSet` is the actual output of this file — `types` (every `@type` entry) plus `arity0` (the subset usable as generic arguments). `TypeOptions` is declared here but not constructed anywhere in this file; it's a shape (`types` + `generic_args`) presumably assembled elsewhere from a `TypeSet`, so if its field semantics need to change, check for a consumer outside this file rather than assuming it's dead code.

`build_type_set(entries: &[Entry]) -> Result<TypeSet, ExpandError>` filters `entries` to `@type`-flagged ones (`e.flags.is_type()`), renders each template via `render_type_text`, and derives `arity0` as: arity-0, not `free_type`, and not flagged `no_arg`. The `no_arg` exclusion is easy to miss — a type can be concrete (arity 0) yet still excluded from the generic-argument pool if its entry set the `no_arg` flag, meaning it's valid standalone but not as a nested generic parameter.

`render_type_text` only accepts `Chunk::Lit` and `Chunk::TypeSlot`; any other chunk kind in a `@type` template (e.g. a stroke-arg or other slot type legal elsewhere in the grammar) produces an `ExpandError` naming the offending chunk kind via `kind_name()`. This is the enforcement point for the invariant that `@type` templates may only contain literals and `%t` markers — no other Pass A/B slot syntax is legal there.